@node BuildArchive "Build Distribution Archives"
 @{b}@{u}Build Distribution Archives@{uu}@{ub} (*NEW in V3.00)

 This function was suggested by Tiziano, thanks for the Idea..

 Use this to build an archive containing all needed files to play the  levels
 you  make. You can use this mainly for sending levels to AmiNET or to put on
 homepages/cd's etc..


 NOTES:
  - The function does NOT check for what actual GFX files is  needed  by  the
    single level, this would have NO meaning 'course the game won't start  if
    any of the files pointed by the setup are missing..
  - It is perfectly legal to create an archive with NO levels,  that'll  only
    include the setup-files..
  - The 2 standard packers uses calls that keeps the paths of the files,  you
    should ensure that the custom call also does that if you use it..
  - The editor compares for new/changed files relating to the original  GAME,
    NOT the original editor config, this  mean  that  the  levels  should  be
    installed 'on-top' of the game to run..
  - The function should find files that have been changed and saved under the
    same name, it does NOT rely on filenames or sizes only, the editor  tries
    to find changed files using a 'checksum' of the file..
  - The function is based on DISC files, that means you  MUST save your setup
    and/or level BEFORE packing the archive if you'd like it included..
  - The function is NOT erasing any previous archive with the same  name,  so
    ensure that the filename is NOT present before packing..

 Options:
  - 'Levels'
      Hehe, tricky ey ?. Simply tick the ones you'd like to include.

  - 'Include Developer files'
      Ticking this will include the special  files  needed  for  editing  the
      level later on, this mean included 3 aditional files for each level..
  - 'Include Game-SetUp'
      Ticking this includes any changed/new gamesetup files in  the  archive,
      this include texts, GFX, SFX, Vector, Objects, etc..

  - 'Archiver'
      Select what archiver you'd like to use:
      'LhA' will use 'LhA a -x %a %f' as command for packing
      'LZx' will use 'Lzx a -x %a %f' as command for packing
      'Custom' uses the command set by a @{"tooltype" link TOOL}..

@endnode
